One question.
Can we have another property to enable "all"?
Sorry mistook this commit with MFABypass interface's commit: https://gerrit.openbmc.org/c/openbmc/phosphor-dbus-interfaces/+/72603.

https://gerrit.openbmc.org/c/openbmc/phosphor-dbus-interfaces/+/72603

In this commit, there is another MFA option listed. Should you add that as well here?
Done
No new InternalFailures.
Done

Why do we need separate properties for each of these?  Reuse the enumerations from Bypass (or maybe move the enumeration here) and add a single property with a set.  I don't want bmcweb code to have to hard-code unique property names.  We should be able to create a map of Redfish enums to dbus enums.

I don't care what the Redfish property was.  We don't want internal code to be just a "Redfish engine" and we don't need all the unique code this causes to have functions needing to be implemented for each property.  Please make this an enabled-status-set.

> Why do we need separate properties for each of these? 

Agreed.  In OpenBMC, I don't think we intend to support any of these in parallel (and the user-specific interfaces don't support that) so lets just make this a "MFA mode" enum rather than a bunch of Bools.

In bmcweb we'll convert that into the various boolean interfaces.
(insert rant about Redfish acceptance criteria here).
Done

Hi Patrick/Ed
I have addressed your comments, can you please review latest patchset?
Why?

If any random value provided which is not present in enumeration
Then d-bus implementation returns invalid argument error
The dbus bindings handle this. You should not need to manually parse strings like this.  Do you have some example code?

ok, I am not aware that D-bus binding handle this error.
will remove InvalidArgument error
Done
Why is this a set?  Can we significantly simplify and just make it so that one authenticator type is allowed at a time?

as per redfish, its array of enums specifying the each MFA factor and multiple factor can be enabled at the same time and using same redfish enum names in D-bus as well so that we dont need to do redfish enum to d-bus enum translations 
We have discussed here to use set.
https://gerrit.openbmc.org/c/openbmc/phosphor-dbus-interfaces/+/72603/9..17/yaml/xyz/openbmc_project/User/MFABypass.interface.yaml#b6

this isn’t Redfish.  we can decide to support a single OTP at a time.
the fact that Redfish looks like it supports multiple in parallel I suspect has more to do with how they organize keys and config rather than actually wanting to support multiple at a time.

this property is generic property not is specific to TOTP authentication, represents what all factor of authentication factors configured as part of MFA, say if we want to support SecurId in future then we dont need to make any changes to this D-bus configuration.

> this property is generic property not is specific to TOTP authentication

We're not going to support both google authenticator and SecurID at the same time on the same system.  If we are, we need a much more complex design than what you proposed.

Not needing to make changes to this isn't a goal.  Lets get the Google authenticator stuff you're intending to add added, and as we have people working on  new protocols, we'll add them as we go forward.

Agree with Ed. When multiple auth types are supported on a single system, then let that person make the necessary changes to these interfaces. For now, we can just keep it for TOTP authentication handling

actually keeping it as set will be useful in extending to new multi-factor authentication factors in future without impacting TOTP MFA implementation.

since we wanted to restrict this configuration to only TOTP MFA for now and open to extend in future. i modified this commit to remove set and allow only one MFA type allowed

Regardless of whether or not that true, lets keep the implementation as simple as we can for the features we intend to support now.  If we need to change in the future we can, and at that time it will be a lot easier to asses whether it makes the code simpler to have this as a set.
Done
We need another property here for "MultiFactorAuthTypesSupported", so that we can build the Redfish interfaces properly for @AllowedValues
I have updated MultiFactorAuthType to have all redfish supported enum values.

But the implementation doesn't necessary support _all_ of those enum values.  We've already made GoogleAuthenticator a Yocto option (and not enabled by default) so by default the AllowedValues should be empty, right?

yes by default this MultiFactorAuth array will be empty.

are you suggesting to have another property like MultiFactorAuthTypesSupported to populate implementation supported enums?
yes.  we need a way to know which enums are supported in this build config.
shall make this property "MultiFactorAuthTypesSupported" array/set which can hold multiple enum values?
Done

ClientCertificate isn't really a multifactor type in the way this interface defines it, it's an auth type, and something completely transparent to dbus at the moment.

I suspect you don't need this here.

ok, there are client certificate schemas under MFA..
for now just wanted to keep all redfish supported enum values

> for now just wanted to keep all redfish supported enum values

If there is no purpose in exposing it on dbus, because it will never have a dbus backend, we shouldn't expose it.
I believe Client certificate is one of multi factor authentication.
please refer https://github.com/openbmc/bmcweb/blob/master/Redfish.md?plain=1#L65
You are giving information tangential to the question.
i mean to clarify that clientCertificate is one of Multi-factor authentication factors and will required to expose on D-bus

MultiFactorAuth in redfish is a namespace/object.  it does not mean that all modes are fulfilled by the same backend.

if you have something in a future design that needs this enum, we can discuss adding it then, but given your design and code that I’ve seen, there’s nothing that implements a client certificate backend.
yeah agreed, we are not implementing clientCertificate  backend right now.
Done
Do these need to call out the actual OTP implementation in the background?  To my understanding, Microsoft OTP versus Google OTP are completely different protocols on the backend.

yeah google/Microsoft authenticators implements Time-based One-time Password (TOTP)
RFC. as per redfish this OneTimePassword authentication is different than Google/Microsoft TOTP based authentication.

Cool, so lets get descriptions here and pointers to the specs for each of these implementations.  Just because Redfish documents the various types in their spec doesn't mean we don't have to document it here.

For example, based on this patch, I have no idea what TOTPAuthenticator and OneTimePasscode are intended to represent.  I should not have to go to the Redfish spec to go figure that out.

Just to be clear, are you going to implement all 5 of these in the immediate future?  Your design doc only called out one.  If not, I'd rather we keep this enumeration to the ones that we will actually have implementations of, and if we add a new type in the future, we can add enumerations over time.  If you plan to immediately implement these 5, then sure, we can start with this, but this enum implies that at some level we have support for all of these.
agree
Description needs to call out that this property is read-only.
Done
Do we need an enumeration for "none" that can be the default?  Otherwise I'm not clear in the interface how we disable OTP.
yes its needed
Default here should be None

I have defined default value for MultiFactorAuth.

 - name: MultiFactorAuth
      type: enum[self.MultiFactorAuthType]
      default: None

do we need to add default value here as well??
Nope, I misread.  This patchset looks fine
Just for completeness, can you add a description here?
Done
Minor nitpick on a description.  Otherwise looks good.
Nit, now that we have "none" please call out that if no entries are supported, this should be an empty set, and should never include None
Done

agreed
